#### Academic Career

Chan's career is a striking illustration of how a profound understanding of [mathematics](/Mathematics) can translate into leadership and influence across diverse academic and scientific spheres. His path has been one of consistent progression, marked by both deep scholarly engagement and significant administrative responsibility.

Before assuming the presidency of the [Hong Kong University of Science and Technology](/Hong_Kong_University_of_Science_and_Technology), Chan held a crucial position at the US [National Science Foundation](/National_Science_Foundation). From 2006 to 2009, he served as the assistant director of the Mathematical and Physical Sciences Directorate. This role is significant, placing him at the helm of directing and shaping research funding and priorities in fundamental scientific fields. It's a position that requires not only a keen intellect but also a strategic vision for the advancement of science.

His association with the [University of California, Los Angeles](/University_of_California,_Los_Angeles) (UCLA) spans many years and roles. Following his postdoctoral research at [Caltech](/California_Institute_of_Technology) as a research fellow, he joined UCLA as a Professor of Mathematics in 1986. His tenure there was marked by increasing leadership responsibilities. He was appointed chair of the Department of Mathematics in 1997, a position that demands both academic prowess and the ability to guide a department of scholars. From 2001 to 2006, he served as the dean of physical sciences, overseeing a broad spectrum of scientific disciplines.

Crucially, Chan was one of the principal investigators instrumental in the successful proposal to the NSF for the establishment of the [Institute for Pure and Applied Mathematics](/Institute_for_Pure_and_Applied_Mathematics) at UCLA. This institute, funded by the NSF, is a significant hub for mathematical research. He served as its director from 2000 to 2001, a period likely focused on solidifying its foundation and setting its initial research agenda.

His scholarly impact is recognized by his listing as an ISI Highly Cited Author in Mathematics by the [ISI Web of Knowledge](/ISI_Web_of_Knowledge), Thomson Scientific Company. This designation is not easily achieved; it signifies that his published works have been frequently cited by other researchers, indicating their influence and importance within the mathematical community.

Since 2009, he has held the distinguished title of professor emeritus of mathematics at UCLA, allowing him to remain connected to the academic world while focusing on his other endeavors. His work has been particularly influential in the application of [mathematics](/Mathematics) to [image processing](/Image_processing), a field that bridges theoretical concepts with tangible, real-world applications.

